FILE: Protesters hold placards during a protest to show their support to fellow miners who filed a lawsuit against mining companies, Johannesburg, 13 October 2015. JOHANNESBURG - The Gauteng High Court in Johannesburg has approved a historic R5-billion settlement agreement in the silicosis case. The legal process involving gold miners affected by lung diseases has stretched over several years. WATCH: New mining charter released The agreement affects people who contracted silicosis or pulmonary tuberculosis during or after being employed at gold mines, from March 1965. The six mining companies paying out are African Rainbow Minerals‚ Anglo American SA‚ AngloGold Ashanti‚ Gold Fields‚ Harmony and Sibanye Stillwater. The companies admit that they failed to take necessary precautions to protect their employees in the past. The claimants will receive between R70,000 and R500,000.